<TITLE> Barapukuria strikers satisfied with govt assurance </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dinajpur, Mar 12 (bdnews24.com)  Locals affected by the Barapukuria coal mine, in Dinajpur, withdrew their hungerstrike on Friday after the government assured them compensation and permanent rehabilitation by June. This was the third day of the hunger-strike. Parbartipur Upazila Nirbahi Officer Mujib-Ul Ferdous said, locals withdrew the strike after the government assurance of compensations for affected locals within June. Those who may be affected till then will also be given compensation. Over 1,000 people of 15 villages, under the banner of the Committee to Protect Life and Property, began a 'fast-unto-death' on Wednesday demanding immediate compensation and permanent rehabilitation from the government for the damage already caused to the area by the mine. Their farmlands had subsided due to underground excavation of coal. As a result, locals said previsouly high ground had now become low land that remained under water through most of the monsoon, making crop cultivation vritually impossible. The hunger strike continued through the second day on Thursday, with at least 50 people falling ill due to severe dehydration. Ibrahim Khalil, convener of the committee told bdnews24.com on Friday that, "The strike was withdrawn due to the government's assurance." Senior officials of the mine and district authorities including Makbul Hossain, Dinajpur's additional deputy commissioner, acting police super Hasan Mohammed Shawkat Ali and Barapukuria coal mine's general manager (mining) Mir Abdul Matin were present when local broke their fast. bdnew
